{"by":"grishka","id":47775513,"kids":[47776264],"parent":47724571,"text":"There was also a Soviet Apple II clone, called Агат (Agat). But iirc, for whatever reason, they couldn&#x27;t clone the 6502, so they built one out of logic ICs, and the thing was too slow to run Apple II software unmodified. Later there was an expansion card with a real imported 6502 that added full compatibility.<p>The USSR did make their own Z80 and 8080 clones later though. There existed an IBM PC compatible built completely out of Soviet-made parts. A lot of fully localized ZX Spectrum clones as well, of varying degree of homebrewness. Those were very popular in the late 80s and early 90s from what I gather, but I&#x27;m too young to have used one myself.","time":1776235407,"type":"comment"}